{"title_page": "Mountains May Depart", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mountains May Depart\n| image          = Mountains May Depart poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = {{Infobox name module\n| chinese        = \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba\n|translation=Old Man of the Mountain River\n| pinyin         = Sh\u0101nh\u00e9 g\u00f9r\u00e9n\n}}\n| director       = [[Jia Zhangke]]\n| producer       = Ren Zhonglun <br> Nathana\u00ebl Karmitz <br> Liu Shiyu <br> Shozo Ichiyama\n| writer         = Jia Zhangke\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on |[title of the original work] |[writer of the original work]}} -->\n| starring       = [[Zhao Tao]] <br> [[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]] <br> Liang Jingdong <br> [[Dong Zijian]]\n| narrator       = <!-- or: | narrators = -->\n| music          = Yoshihiro Hanno\n| cinematography = Yu Lik Wai\n| editing        = Matthieu Laclau\n| production companies = Xstream Pictures<br>Shanghai Film Group<br>MK2\n| distributors   = Sihai Distribution Association (China)<ref name=cbooo/><br>Tianjin Maoyan Media (China)<ref name=cbooo/><br>Ad Vitam (France)\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|5|20|[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2015|10|30|China|2015|12|23|France|2016|4|23|Japan|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 131 minutes\n| country        = China<br>France<br>Japan\n| language       = Mandarin\n| budget         = \n| gross          = {{CNY|32.22 million}} (China)<br />{{USD|79,768}} (United States)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=mountainsmaydepart.htm |title=Mountains May Depart |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref><!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''Mountains May Depart''''' ({{zh|\u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba}}) is a 2015 [[drama film]] directed by [[Jia Zhangke]].  The film is Jia's eighth feature film.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://movie.douban.com/subject/25890005/|title= \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba (2015)|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= movie.douban.com|publisher= [[douban.com]]|language= Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/shanghai-film-group-reveals-forthcoming-projects|title= Shanghai Film Group reveals forthcoming projects|author= Kevin Ma|date= 13 February 2015|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= [[Film Business Asia]]|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150213203804/http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/shanghai-film-group-reveals-forthcoming-projects|archivedate= 13 February 2015|df= dmy-all}}</ref> It competed for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/article/61306.html |title=2015 Official Selection |accessdate=16 April 2015 |work=Cannes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/61347.html|title=Screenings Guide|work=Festival de Cannes|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> It has also been selected to be shown in the Special Presentations section of the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"ScreenDaily\">{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562# |title=Toronto to open with 'Demolition'; world premieres for 'Trumbo', 'The Program' |date=28 July 2015 |accessdate=28 July 2015 |work=ScreenDaily}}</ref> It was released in China on 30 October 2015.<ref name=cbooo/>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is divided into three parts. The first part is set in the medium-sized town of [[Fenyang]] (in the northern [[Shanxi]] province) in 1999. 25-year-old shopkeeper Tao (Zhao Tao) is torn between two suitors. Jingsheng ([[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]]) is a well-off gas station owner whom she has little connection with but could drastically improve her material living conditions. She feels closer to Liangzi (Liang Jingdong), a poor laborer in a local coal mine. When confronted by both men, Tao decides to marry Jingsheng in the hope of leaving Fenyang.\n\nIn 2014, Tao is now divorced from Jingsheng and still living in Fenyang, running the prosperous gas station and being a prominent and generous woman in the city. Jingsheng has since remarried and lives in Shanghai, and has become wealthy from investments. Liangzi works as a miner near [[Handan]], in the neighboring province of [[Hebei]], and has gotten ill. Most of the second act focuses on Tao and Jingsheng's son, Daole (pronounced Dollar in English) aged 7, who comes to visit her for the funeral of her father. Tao is upset by Daole's distance, which she acknowledges is due to their cultural differences - a product of Jingsheng's fascination with globalization. Tao, knowing they are fated to be apart, decides to ride the slow train with Daole, instead of sending him on a plane back to Shanghai. As a parting gift, Tao makes Daole a set of keys for her house so that he can return to his mother's home whenever he wants.\n\nIn 2025, Daole (now currently called Dollar) is attending college in Australia. He is constantly fighting with his father over his desire to drop out of college and have the freedom he was never granted in his childhood. He meets Mia, his Chinese language teacher, an older woman for whom he develops feelings and eventually begins a relationship with. Dollar shares with Mia how he still carries the keys his mother gave him when he was a young boy, and that he fears she may die, even though they have not talked for years. Mia convinces him to fly back to China with her so that he can see Tao. The film ends with Tao dancing to \"[[Go West (song)|Go West]]\", recalling the beginning of the film when, as a young woman, she was dancing merrily with all of her then fellows (making waves with their arms, \"wave\" being incidentally the translation of the first name \"Tao\" in English), full of hope for a better life. Any reunion with Daole (Dollar) is not seen.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Zhao Tao]]<ref name=variety>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/film/news/chinas-jia-zhangke-plans-mountains-trek-1201185965/|title= China\u2019s Jia Zhangke Plans \u2018Mountains\u2019 Trek (EXCLUSIVE)|author= Patrick Frater|date= 19 May 2014|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n*[[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]]\n*Liang Jingdong\n*[[Dong Zijian]]\n*[[Sylvia Chang]]\n*Rong Zishan\n*Liang Yonghao\n*Liu Lu\n*Yuan Wenqian\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film earned {{CNY|32.22 million}} at the Chinese box office.<ref name=cbooo>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbooo.cn/m/627766|title= \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba\uff082015\uff09|accessdate= 15 February 2016|work= cbooo.cn|language= Chinese}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Mountains May Depart'' holds a 79/100 average on review aggregation site [[Metacritic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mountains-may-depart |title=''Mountains May Depart'' Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote, \"Jia Zhang-ke\u2019s ''Mountains May Depart'' is a mysterious and in its way staggeringly ambitious piece of work from a film-maker whose creativity is evolving before our eyes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/20/mountains-may-depart-review-jia-zhang-ke-scales-new-heights-with-futurist-drama|title= Mountains May Depart review: Jia Zhang-ke scales new heights with futurist drama|author= [[Peter Bradshaw]]|date= 20 May 2015|accessdate= 25 May 2015|work= [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' states \"''Mountains May Depart'' is never less than a work of soaring ambition and deeply felt humanism, as Jia longs not so much to turn back the hands of time, but to ever so slightly slow them down.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/mountains-may-depart-cannes-film-review-1201501026/|title= Cannes Film Review: \u2018Mountains May Depart\u2019|author= Scott Foundas|date= 19 May 2015|accessdate=25 May 2015|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Derek Elley]] of ''[[Film Business Asia]]'' gave it a 5 out of 10, calling the film a \"weakly written saga of friendship [that] goes way off the rails in the final part.\"<ref name=Elley>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/mountains-may-depart|title= Mountains May Depart|author= [[Derek Elley]]|date= 21 May 2015|accessdate= 24 May 2015|work= [[Film Business Asia]]}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n* \"[[Go West (song)|Go West]]\" (1993) by the [[Pet Shop Boys]] <ref name=\"LT\">{{in lang|fr}} Antoine Duplan, [http://www.letemps.ch/culture/2016/01/26/dela-montagnes-argent-ne-bonheur-chine \"\u00ab Au-del\u00e0 des montagnes \u00bb : l\u2019argent ne fait pas le bonheur de la Chine\"], ''[[Le Temps]]'', Tuesday 26 January 2016 (page visited on 3 February 2016).</ref>\n* \"[[Sally Yeh discography#1990|Take care]]\" ({{zh|\u73cd\u91cd}}, 1990) by [[Sally Yeh]] ({{zh|\u8449\u5029\u6587}})<ref name=LT/>\nGo West plays a prominent role in the film, as the film opens to a scene on New Year's Eve 1999 with Tao dancing to the song and closes in 2025 with a scene of Tao crying and dancing to the song near the old pagoda. In an interview with ''AV Club'' Zhangke states that he was attempting to evoke a \"collective history for that generation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://film.avclub.com/director-jia-zhangke-on-technology-relationships-and-1798244155|title=Director Jia Zhangke on technology, relationships, and Pet Shop Boys|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=Film|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|3740778}}\n*{{rottentomatoes|mountains_may_depart_2016}}\n*{{metacritic film|mountains-may-depart}}\n*{{mojo title|mountainsmaydepart}}\n\n{{Jia Zhangke}}\n{{Portal bar|China|Film}}\n\n[[Category:2015 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jia Zhangke]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2025]]\n[[Category:Films set in Australia]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Australia]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese drama films]]\n[[Category:Tianjin Maoyan Media films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mountains May Depart\n| image          = Mountains May Depart poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = {{Infobox name module\n| chinese        = \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba\n|translation=Old Man of the Mountain River\n| pinyin         = Sh\u0101nh\u00e9 g\u00f9r\u00e9n\n}}\n| director       = [[Jia Zhangke]]\n| producer       = Ren Zhonglun <br> Nathana\u00ebl Karmitz <br> Liu Shiyu <br> Shozo Ichiyama\n| writer         = Jia Zhangke\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on |[title of the original work] |[writer of the original work]}} -->\n| starring       = [[Zhao Tao]] <br> [[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]] <br> Liang Jingdong <br> [[Dong Zijian]]\n| narrator       = <!-- or: | narrators = -->\n| music          = Yoshihiro Hanno\n| cinematography = Yu Lik Wai\n| editing        = Matthieu Laclau\n| production companies = Xstream Pictures<br>Shanghai Film Group<br>MK2\n| distributors   = Sihai Distribution Association (China)<ref name=cbooo/><br>Tianjin Maoyan Media (China)<ref name=cbooo/><br>Ad Vitam (France)\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|5|20|[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2015|10|30|China|2015|12|23|France|2016|4|23|Japan|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 131 minutes\n| country        = China<br>France<br>Japan\n| language       = Mandarin\n| budget         = \n| gross          = {{CNY|32.22 million}} (China)<br />{{USD|79,768}} (United States)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=mountainsmaydepart.htm |title=Mountains May Depart |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref><!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''Mountains May Depart''''' ({{zh|\u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba}}) is a 2015 [[drama film]] directed by [[Jia Zhangke]].  The film is Jia's eighth feature film.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://movie.douban.com/subject/25890005/|title= \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba (2015)|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= movie.douban.com|publisher= [[douban.com]]|language= Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/shanghai-film-group-reveals-forthcoming-projects|title= Shanghai Film Group reveals forthcoming projects|author= Kevin Ma|date= 13 February 2015|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= [[Film Business Asia]]|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150213203804/http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/shanghai-film-group-reveals-forthcoming-projects|archivedate= 13 February 2015|df= dmy-all}}</ref> It competed for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/article/61306.html |title=2015 Official Selection |accessdate=16 April 2015 |work=Cannes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/61347.html|title=Screenings Guide|work=Festival de Cannes|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> It has also been selected to be shown in the Special Presentations section of the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"ScreenDaily\">{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562# |title=Toronto to open with 'Demolition'; world premieres for 'Trumbo', 'The Program' |date=28 July 2015 |accessdate=28 July 2015 |work=ScreenDaily}}</ref> It was released in China on 30 October 2015.<ref name=cbooo/>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is divided into three parts. The first part is set in the medium-sized town of [[Fenyang]] (in the northern [[Shanxi]] province) in 1999. 25-year-old shopkeeper Tao (Zhao Tao) is torn between two suitors. Jingsheng ([[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]]) is a well-off gas station owner whom she has little connection with but could drastically improve her material living conditions. She feels closer to Liangzi (Liang Jingdong), a poor laborer in a local coal mine. When confronted by both men, Tao decides to marry Jingsheng in the hope of leaving Fenyang.\n\nIn 2014, Tao is now divorced from Jingsheng and still living in Fenyang, running the prosperous gas station and being a prominent and generous woman in the city. Jingsheng has since remarried and lives in Shanghai, and has become wealthy from investments. Liangzi works as a miner near [[Handan]], in the neighboring province of [[Hebei]], and has gotten ill. Most of the second act focuses on Tao and Jingsheng's son, Daole (pronounced Dollar in English) aged 7, who comes to visit her for the funeral of her father. Tao is upset by Daole's distance, which she acknowledges is due to their cultural differences - a product of Jingsheng's fascination with globalization. Tao, knowing they are fated to be apart, decides to ride the slow train with Daole, instead of sending him on a plane back to Shanghai. As a parting gift, Tao makes Daole a set of keys for her house so that he can return to his mother's home whenever he wants.\n\nIn 2025, Daole (now currently called Dollar) is attending college in Australia. He is constantly fighting with his father over his desire to drop out of college and have the freedom he was never granted in his childhood. He meets Mia, his Chinese language teacher, an older woman for whom he develops feelings and eventually begins a relationship with. Dollar shares with Mia how he still carries the keys his mother gave him when he was a young boy, and that he fears she may die, even though they have not talked for years. Mia convinces him to fly back to China with her so that he can see Tao. The film ends with Tao dancing to \"[[Go West (song)|Go West]]\", recalling the beginning of the film when a young woman, she was dancing merrily with all of her then fellows (making waves with their arms, \"wave\" being incidentally the translation of the first name \"Tao\" in English), full of hope for a better life. Any reunion with Daole (Dollar) is not seen.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Zhao Tao]]<ref name=variety>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/film/news/chinas-jia-zhangke-plans-mountains-trek-1201185965/|title= China\u2019s Jia Zhangke Plans \u2018Mountains\u2019 Trek (EXCLUSIVE)|author= Patrick Frater|date= 19 May 2014|accessdate= 13 February 2015|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n*[[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]]\n*Liang Jingdong\n*[[Dong Zijian]]\n*[[Sylvia Chang]]\n*Rong Zishan\n*Liang Yonghao\n*Liu Lu\n*Yuan Wenqian\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film earned {{CNY|32.22 million}} at the Chinese box office.<ref name=cbooo>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbooo.cn/m/627766|title= \u5c71\u6cb3\u6545\u4eba\uff082015\uff09|accessdate= 15 February 2016|work= cbooo.cn|language= Chinese}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Mountains May Depart'' holds a 79/100 average on review aggregation site [[Metacritic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mountains-may-depart |title=''Mountains May Depart'' Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote, \"Jia Zhang-ke\u2019s ''Mountains May Depart'' is a mysterious and in its way staggeringly ambitious piece of work from a film-maker whose creativity is evolving before our eyes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/20/mountains-may-depart-review-jia-zhang-ke-scales-new-heights-with-futurist-drama|title= Mountains May Depart review: Jia Zhang-ke scales new heights with futurist drama|author= [[Peter Bradshaw]]|date= 20 May 2015|accessdate= 25 May 2015|work= [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' states \"''Mountains May Depart'' is never less than a work of soaring ambition and deeply felt humanism, as Jia longs not so much to turn back the hands of time, but to ever so slightly slow them down.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/mountains-may-depart-cannes-film-review-1201501026/|title= Cannes Film Review: \u2018Mountains May Depart\u2019|author= Scott Foundas|date= 19 May 2015|accessdate=25 May 2015|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Derek Elley]] of ''[[Film Business Asia]]'' gave it a 5 out of 10, calling the film a \"weakly written saga of friendship [that] goes way off the rails in the final part.\"<ref name=Elley>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/mountains-may-depart|title= Mountains May Depart|author= [[Derek Elley]]|date= 21 May 2015|accessdate= 24 May 2015|work= [[Film Business Asia]]}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n* \"[[Go West (song)|Go West]]\" (1993) by the [[Pet Shop Boys]] <ref name=\"LT\">{{in lang|fr}} Antoine Duplan, [http://www.letemps.ch/culture/2016/01/26/dela-montagnes-argent-ne-bonheur-chine \"\u00ab Au-del\u00e0 des montagnes \u00bb : l\u2019argent ne fait pas le bonheur de la Chine\"], ''[[Le Temps]]'', Tuesday 26 January 2016 (page visited on 3 February 2016).</ref>\n* \"[[Sally Yeh discography#1990|Take care]]\" ({{zh|\u73cd\u91cd}}, 1990) by [[Sally Yeh]] ({{zh|\u8449\u5029\u6587}})<ref name=LT/>\nGo West plays a prominent role in the film, as the film opens to a scene on New Year's Eve 1999 with Tao dancing to the song and closes in 2025 with a scene of Tao crying and dancing to the song near the old pagoda. In an interview with ''AV Club'' Zhangke states that he was attempting to evoke a \"collective history for that generation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://film.avclub.com/director-jia-zhangke-on-technology-relationships-and-1798244155|title=Director Jia Zhangke on technology, relationships, and Pet Shop Boys|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|work=Film|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|3740778}}\n*{{rottentomatoes|mountains_may_depart_2016}}\n*{{metacritic film|mountains-may-depart}}\n*{{mojo title|mountainsmaydepart}}\n\n{{Jia Zhangke}}\n{{Portal bar|China|Film}}\n\n[[Category:2015 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jia Zhangke]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2025]]\n[[Category:Films set in Australia]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Australia]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese drama films]]\n[[Category:Tianjin Maoyan Media films]]\n", "name_user": "Koichirose", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mountains_May_Depart"}
{"title_page": "Ludum Dare", "text_new": "[[File:New Ludum Dare Logo.png|thumb|New Ludum Dare Logo]]\n[[File:Ludum Dare logo (old).svg|thumb|alt=Old Ludum Dare logo|Old Ludum Dare logo]]\n\n'''Ludum Dare''' ('''LD''') ({{IPA-la|\u02c8lu\u02d0d\u0169\u02d0 \u02c8dar\u025b|classical}}, meaning 'to give a game',<ref>{{cite web|title=A shocking question!|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/2010/08/18/a-shocking-question/|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=December 14, 2013|date=August 18, 2010}}</ref> also referenced as '''LDJAM''') is an [[Game jam|accelerated]] [[video game development]] [[competition]]. It was founded by Geoff Howland and was first held in April 2002.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=About Ludum Dare|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/about-ludum-dare/|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> It is currently run by Mike Kasprzak, who has been part of the team since the beginning.<ref name=\":1\" /> Participants are required to create a [[video game]] that fits within a given theme in two or three days.<ref>{{cite web|last=Senior|first=Tom|title=Ludum Dare 19 results announced|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2011/01/12/ludum-dare-19-results-announced/|work=PC Gamer|publisher=Future|accessdate=December 14, 2013|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Mark|title=Time Pygmy Wins Ludum Dare 19 Indie Game Challenge|url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2011/01/ludum-dare-time-pygmy/|work=Wired|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=December 14, 2013|date=January 15, 2011}}</ref> A unique feature of this competition is that participants often release a [[time-lapse]] video of the development of their game.<ref name=timelapse>{{cite web|last=W.|first=Tim|title=Ludum Dare 18 Timelapse Videos|url=http://www.indiegames.com/2010/08/ludum_dare_18_timelapse_videos.html|work=Indie Games|publisher=UBM Tech|accessdate=December 14, 2013|date=August 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nLudum Dare was originally only an [[Internet forum]]. The first competition&mdash;often referred to as \"Ludum Dare Zero\"&mdash;was held in April 2002, with 18 participants. Its popularity turned the focus towards the competitions rather than the forum. The time limit was subsequently increased to 48 hours, because 24 hours were decided to be too few.<ref name=intel1>{{cite web|last=Boswell|first=Wendy|title=Get Your Game On with Ludum Dare: Interview with Mike Kasprzak (Part 1)|url=http://software.intel.com/en-us/blogs/2013/09/30/get-your-game-on-with-ludum-dare-interview-with-mike-kasprzak-part-1|work=Intel|accessdate=December 15, 2013|date=September 30, 2013}}</ref> Since 2011 the competition has seen significant annual increases in numbers of game submissions, partly owing to the public awareness of [[Minecraft]] designer [[Markus Persson]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Peter|title=Ludum Dare for Rubyists: An Online 48 Hour Game Coding Competition|url=http://www.rubyinside.com/ludum-dare-for-rubyists-an-online-48-hour-game-coding-competition-5687.html|work=Ruby Inside|accessdate=December 15, 2013|date=December 13, 2011}}</ref> who has participated seven times.<ref>{{cite web|title=Notch|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/author/notch/|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2014, the event was very informal as the Ludum Dare team worked on it in their spare time. Due to the increasing number of contestants, long-time organizer Mike Kasprzak announced in September 2014 that he would attempt at setting up a business model allowing him to work full-time on the project.<ref name=\"ldfuture\">{{cite web|url=http://gamasutra.com/view/news/225663/Ludum_Dare_organizer_ponders_the_game_jams_future.php|work=Gamasutra|title=Ludum Dare organizer ponders the game jam's future|date=September 16, 2014}}</ref> Charging for Ludum Dare is however \"out of question\",<ref name=\"ldfuture\" /> and money is currently exclusively raised through donations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ludumdare.com/compo/2014/09/26/the-future-of-ludum-dare-part-3/|work=Ludum Dare|title=The Future of Ludum Dare (Part 3) \u2013 The Beginning|date=September 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring Ludum Dare 35 in April 2016, an announcement acknowledged various issues regarding the game jam's rating system. In particular, it explained that some users had attempted to artificially boost their game ratings with alternative accounts. As a consequence of this problem, future Ludum Dare events were indefinitely cancelled pending a replacement website being constructed for hosting the game jam.<ref>http://ludumdare.com/compo/2016/06/08/well-this-is-awkward-2/</ref> This led to a community backlash, and the game jam in August 2016 went ahead regardless, organized by website administrator and long-time community member ''sorceress''. In respect of the complaints previously raised, the community decided by referendum to forego the game rating phase after the game jam. So uniquely, there were no winners for that one event.<ref>http://ludumdare.com/compo/2016/06/09/august-ld-you-decide/</ref>\n\nStarting in Ludum Dare 44, the schedule was changed to run twice per year in April and October due to organizer Mike Kasprzak struggling to keep up<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ldjam.com/events/ludum-dare/42/placeholder/results-for-ludum-dare-42|website=ldjam.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n== Competition structure ==\n\nCurrently, Ludum Dare is held two times a year.<ref>https://ldjam.com/events/ludum-dare/43/$120416/results-for-ludum-dare-43</ref> In the week preceding each competition suggested themes are subject to votes by prospective participants. A theme is subsequently announced<ref name=intel3>{{cite web|last=Boswell|first=Wendy|title=Get Your Game On with Ludum Dare: Interview with Mike Kasprzak (Part 3)|url=http://software.intel.com/en-us/blogs/2013/10/04/get-your-game-on-with-ludum-dare-interview-with-mike-kasprzak-part-3|work=Intel|accessdate=December 15, 2013|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref> before participants are given 48 hours to create a [[video game]] (although [[board games]] or similar are accepted<ref name=guide>{{cite web|title=Rules and Guide|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/rules/|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref>) that fits within it.  All game code and content must be created during the competition and by a single person, and [[source code]] is encouraged to be included. During the event many participants record multiple [[screenshot]]s of the development of their game to later produce a [[time-lapse]] video.<ref name=timelapse /> In addition, many broadcast a live [[streaming video|video stream]],<ref name=intel2>{{cite web|last=Boswell|first=Wendy|title=Get Your Game On with Ludum Dare: Interview with Mike Kasprzak (Part 2)|url=http://software.intel.com/en-us/blogs/2013/10/02/get-your-game-on-with-ludum-dare-interview-with-mike-kasprzak-part-2|work=Intel|accessdate=December 15, 2013|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref> particularly since April 2013, when a widget showing Ludum Dare video streams hosted on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] was added to the Ludum Dare website.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kasprzak|first=Mike|title=Streaming Widget Alpha 2|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/2013/04/13/streaming-widget-alpha-2/|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=December 15, 2013|date=April 13, 2013}}</ref> After the end of the competition participants are given three weeks to play and rate other submitted games to determine the winners.<ref name=intel3 /> There are no physical or cash prizes, but each participant retains full ownership of their game<ref name=guide/>&mdash;some have achieved financial success after developing their initial submission.<ref name=intel2 />\n\nAs of the 18th edition of the competition, which was held in August 2010, a more relaxed version called the \"Jam\" was introduced. The Jam, which allows development teams, private source code and extended development time of 72 hours, takes place concurrently with the solo competition.<ref name=guide />\n\nA smaller competition called \"Mini Ludum Dare\" is held during months without a Ludum Dare. These are each hosted by a veteran participant who is free to decide the theme within which the games must fit.<ref name=intel2 /> The rules are generally the same as in Ludum Dare, but the 48-hour limitation is usually ignored in favor of late participation.\n\nEvery October Ludum Dare hosts the October Challenge, which challenges people to \"Finish a game,  take it to market, and earn $1\".<ref>{{cite web|title=October Challenge 2014|url=http://ludumdare.com/compo/2014/09/29/october-challenge-2014/|accessdate=November 1, 2014}}</ref> Participants have 31 days to upload a link to their game to the website. The event is not competitive and is just a small event to encourage game development from people who do not make money from their games regularly.\n\n== Results ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|No. !! rowspan=2|Month !! rowspan=2|Theme (bonus) !! colspan=2|Participants !! colspan=2|Compo winner !! colspan=2|Jam winner !! rowspan=2|Ref.\n|-\n! Sign-ups !! Submissions !! Developer !! Game !! Developer(s) !! Game\n|-\n| 0\u2020 || April 2002 || Indirect interaction || || 18 || Endurion || ''Magnetic Fields'' || || ||\n|-\n| 1 || July 2002 || Guardian || 136 || 46 || Hamumu || ''Scarecrow: Heart of Straw'' || || ||\n|-\n| 2 || November 2002 || Construction/destruction (sheep) || 116 || 49 || ShredWheat || ''Sheep Town'' || || ||\n|-\n| 3 || April 2003 || Preparation &ndash; Set it up, let it go || 84 || || || || || ||\n|-\n| 4 || April 2004 || Infection || 341 || 66 || randomnine || ''Commies!'' || || ||\n|-\n| 5 || October 2004 || Random || 93 || || Jolle || ''Random Dungeon Exploration'' || || ||\n|-\n| 6 || April 2005 || Light and darkness || 143 || 52 || Jolle || ''Uplighter'' || || ||\n|-\n| 7 || December 2005 || Growth || || 27 || Jolle || ''The People'' || || ||\n|-\n| 8 || April 2006 || Swarms || 150 || 66 || || || || ||\n|-\n| 8.5\u2020 || January 2007 || Moon/anti-text || || || || || || ||\n|-\n| 9 || April 2007 || Build the level you play || || || DrPetter || ''Spatzap aka N/A'' || || ||\n|-\n| 10 || December 2007 || Chain reaction || 158 || 51 || Hamumu || ''Short Fuse'' || || ||\n|-\n| 10.5 || February 2008 || Weird/unexpected/surprise || || || || || || ||\n|-\n| 11 || April 2008 || Minimalist || || 71 || mrfun/SethR || ''Strong AI'' || || ||\n|-\n| 12 || August 2008 || The tower || || 57 || Hamumu || ''Rise Of The Owls'' || || ||\n|-\n| 13 || December 2008 || Roads || || 59 || increpare || ''Rara Racer'' || || ||\n|-\n| 14 || April 2009 || Advancing wall of doom || || 123 || mrfun/SethR || ''Mind Wall'' || || ||\n|-\n| 15 || August 2009 || Caverns || || 144 || ChevyRay || ''Beacon'' || || ||\n|-\n| 16 || December 2009 || Exploration || || 121 || chuchino || ''Cat Planet'' || || ||\n|-\n| 17 || April 2010 || Islands || || 204 || xerus || ''Gaiadi'' || || ||\n|-\n| 18 || August 2010 || Enemies as weapons || || 172 || invicticide || ''Fail-Deadly'' || || ||\n|-\n| 19 || December 2010 || Discovery || || 242 || deepnight (S\u00e9bastien B\u00e9nard)|| ''Time Pygmy'' || || ||\n|-\n| 20 || April 2011 || It's dangerous to go alone! Take this! || || 288 || deepnight (S\u00e9bastien B\u00e9nard) || ''Appy 1000mg'' || || ||\n|-\n| 21 || August 2011 || Escape || || 599 || Chevy Ray Johnston || ''Flee Buster'' || Ian Brock<br />Josh Schonstal<br />Guerin McMurry || ''Escape'' || <ref>{{cite web|last=McDaniel|first=Walter|title=Ludum Dare 21 results- compo|url=http://www.nerd-age.com/ludum-dare-21-results-compo/|work=Nerd Age|accessdate=January 9, 2014|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ludum Dare 21 Results- Jam Edition|url=http://www.nerd-age.com/ludum-dare-21-results-jam-competition/|work=Nerd Age|accessdate=January 9, 2014|date=September 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ludum Dare 21|url=http://www.ludumdare.com/compo/ludum-dare-21/?action=preview|work=Ludum Dare|accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 22 